Hey, just wanted to circle back on M54's cancel today with some more details, if y'all were interested. Talked with the AC on the sequence and decision. He said that the crew was already delayed in the step because crew comm wasn't present to pick up comsec. After getting to the jet, mx told the crew that the ER was good but they had to go black jet quick. At that point, the transloading was paused between the Rhino team handling haz cargo and the ATOC team. When the APU was shut down, the door stayed cracked partially open for approx 2 mins. "APU door disag" stayed on the WAP. Mx inspection revealed that the prox sensor on the door was corroded. Mx informed the crew that there was one of two fixes: safe the door or replace the sensor. Each fix was billed as a 1.5 to 2 hour fix. At that point, the Pro Sup told the crew he wasn't aware of the door issue the night previous when it had been written up (APU door disag has been a constant issue for other crews and even annunciated in the high speed regime on a takeoff). Pro Sup then said he was only aware of it when mx got to the jet at 1000Z (crew got there at 1100Z). He then left for a meeting. During this time, mx at the jet passed an ETIC to ATOC and Rhino, but not to the crew. ATOC decided to go service other jets in sequence, and Rhino took the haz cargo back to the loading shed. Power was then applied to the jet with a power cart, but without air, an avionics overheat occurred. So without a solid ETIC, mx giving an unofficial timeline of 2 hours at takeoff time, collective crew fatigue, and no ATOC/rhino presence at the jet (they would show to load after the mx was performed), the AC elected to cancel. Contributing to the decision was the fact that the delay to complete mx and then load would push a takeoff time pushing well past maximum FDP for their basic crew.
